#Testing Normality

library(nortest)
#Kolvmogrov-Smirnov Test Indicates Normal
ks.test(rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm), "pnorm") # p-val is 0.8674, D = 0.126 
## 
##  Exact one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)
## D = 0.12645, p-value = 0.8674
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided
#Indicates non-normality, could be because of the low observations since
#QQplot and KS test indicates otherwise
#Shapiro-Wilkes Test
shapiro.test(rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)) #p-val = 0.0016 , W = 0.818
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)
## W = 0.81775, p-value = 0.001609
##Anderson- Darling Test
#p-value is < 0.05 evidence shows non-normality
ad.test(rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)) #p-val = 0.000503, A.D = 1.5002
## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)
## A = 1.5002, p-value = 0.000503
#cramer-von TEst

#p-value < 0.05 evidence indicates non-normality
cvm.test(rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)) #p-val = 0.000913
## 
##  Cramer-von Mises normality test
## 
## data:  rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)
## W = 0.25629, p-value = 0.000913
#Lillies Test

lillie.test(rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)) #p-val = 0.003724
## 
##  Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) normality test
## 
## data:  rstudent(Japan_b.rate.mlm)
## D = 0.24005, p-value = 0.003724
Japan_b.rate.mlm%>%
  get_regression_points()%>%
